        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">7, Great Charles St. | Birmingham.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 16</date>
                    <salute>My Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Let me acknowledge your reference, with thanks for your thoughtfulness<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I have had some correspondence with Prof Blackie &amp; asked him about my new substance. He made some ingenious suggestions, but the results were awkward and I prefer “Azerin” to any other word I can coin.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>There is no doubt that this substance will be found in many places now that we know of its existence.</p>
<p>It is very curious. A temp of 212<hi rend="superscript">o</hi> does not interfere with its properties, but alcohol does. It dries into a straw coloured substance, transparent, but as soon as you remove heat &amp; allow the access of air it absorbs very many times its bulk of water—probably over 30 or 40 times its bulk.</p>
<p>Please do not answer this.</p>
<p>Yours faithfully, | Lawson Tait.</p>
<p>Winter has put a stop to my enquiries in many directions when I think there is much to be done.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10244.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Lawson Tait, 6 November [1875]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD’s letter has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_467.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Stuart Blackie</ref> was professor of Greek at <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1454.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edinburgh University</ref>. Tait wanted to name a substance that he believed he had isolated in the digestive fluid of insectivorous plants (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10244.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Lawson Tait, 6 November [1875]</ref>).</note>
